236
00:26:55,778 --> 00:26:59,220
Well, then you must know
how we all feel down here.

237
00:26:59,324 --> 00:27:02,974
We don't take to outsiders
tellin' us how to live our lives.

238
00:27:03,078 --> 00:27:05,685
And I'm here to tell ya,
our nigras were happy...

239
00:27:05,790 --> 00:27:09,648
...till those beatnik college kids
came down here stirrin' things up.

240
00:27:09,753 --> 00:27:12,985
Before that, there wasn't
anybody complainin'.

241
00:27:13,090 --> 00:27:15,697
Nobody dared.

242
00:27:16,427 --> 00:27:19,660
We got a real peaceful
community down here, Anderson.

243
00:27:19,764 --> 00:27:24,457
Course, they're just like any other folks,
I reckon, when you push 'em too far.

244
00:27:24,561 --> 00:27:29,462
The way I figure it,
it's like three sticks of old dynamite.

245
00:27:29,567 --> 00:27:34,260
You shake it up... and we're gonna
be scrapin' bodies off the street.

246
00:27:35,407 --> 00:27:39,682
I'm just here to investigate the missing
three kids, ask some questions.

247
00:27:39,787 --> 00:27:41,977
If this all boiled down to gravy...

248
00:27:42,081 --> 00:27:45,209
...there wouldn't be enough
to cover a chicken-fried steak.

249
00:27:45,314 --> 00:27:52,405
Them kids you're lookin' for? I'd bet you a
shiny new dime they're in Chicago now...

250
00:27:52,509 --> 00:27:57,828
...drinkin' a cold beer and havin' a laugh
about the commotion they stirred up here.

251
00:27:57,932 --> 00:27:59,809
Well, I sure hope so.

252
00:27:59,914 --> 00:28:04,502
You can tell your bosses people got
the wrong idea about the South.

253
00:28:05,545 --> 00:28:07,631
You know what I'm talkin' about.

254
00:28:07,735 --> 00:28:11,281
Everybody runnin' around ragged,
backwards and illiterate...

255
00:28:11,385 --> 00:28:15,244
...eatin' sowbelly and corn pone
three times a day.

256
00:28:15,348 --> 00:28:19,519
Simple fact is, Anderson,
we got two cultures down here.

257
00:28:19,624 --> 00:28:23,482
White culture and a coloured culture.

258
00:28:23,586 --> 00:28:27,966
That's the way it always has been.
That's the way it always will be.

259
00:28:28,071 --> 00:28:32,659
- The rest of America don't see it that way.
- The rest of America don't mean jack shit.

260
00:28:32,763 --> 00:28:35,058
You in Mississippi now.

261
00:28:35,683 --> 00:28:37,769
Oh, that's for sure!

262
00:28:40,168 --> 00:28:43,922
- What's the score, Mr Barber?
- St Louis on top, five to nothing.

263
00:28:44,026 --> 00:28:46,633
- What inning is it?
- Bottom of the seventh.

264
00:28:46,738 --> 00:28:50,179
- You like baseball, Anderson?
- Yeah, I do. You know...

265
00:28:52,056 --> 00:28:56,853
...it's the only time when a black man
can wave a stick at a white man...

266
00:28:57,375 --> 00:28:59,669
...and not start a riot.

267
00:29:15,625 --> 00:29:17,502
Sir.

268
00:29:17,606 --> 00:29:21,048
We checked on the plate, sir.
Clayton Townley.

269
00:29:21,152 --> 00:29:25,219
Townley. Grand Wizard of
the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.

270
00:29:25,323 --> 00:29:28,139
That's him. And we have a lead on the car.

271
00:29:28,243 --> 00:29:31,997
A Choctaw on the reservation
thinks he knows where it is.

272
00:29:32,102 --> 00:29:33,353
Good.

273
00:29:49,413 --> 00:29:52,020
You have an appointment next Tuesday?

274
00:29:52,124 --> 00:29:54,210
I'll see you then. Bye-bye.

275
00:30:21,116 --> 00:30:23,723
Afternoon, ladies.

276
00:30:23,827 --> 00:30:26,539
- Can I help you?
- Well, yes, you can.

277
00:30:26,643 --> 00:30:30,501
I tell you, I just...
I hate the way I look. You know?

278
00:30:30,606 --> 00:30:34,256
What do you think? A permanent wave,
maybe? Or a bleach job?

279
00:30:36,029 --> 00:30:40,096
- That looks good. Was it done in here?
- No. Jackson.

280
00:30:40,200 --> 00:30:45,727
A wig's your only hope, hon. You won't
be able to do much with that cue ball.

281
00:30:47,500 --> 00:30:51,150
If you wanna ask us some questions,
this is where you'll hear it all.

282
00:30:51,254 --> 00:30:53,444
Yeah, matter of fact, I do.

283
00:30:54,383 --> 00:30:57,928
I was wonderin' who that gentleman was
that just drove in over there.

284
00:30:58,033 --> 00:31:02,308
- I know that isn't President Johnson.
- His name's Townley. Clayton Townley.

285
00:31:02,413 --> 00:31:06,167
- Are you one of them FBI gentlemen?
- Yes, ma'am, I am.

286
00:31:06,271 --> 00:31:11,381
Well, I think it's a shame if those two kids
are dead. But I sure hope you find 'em.

287
00:31:11,485 --> 00:31:15,761
Thank you. Actually, three kids are
missin'. There's a coloured kid also.

288
00:31:16,178 --> 00:31:20,663
Do you think your people'd be down here
if it weren't for those two white boys?

289
00:31:20,767 --> 00:31:22,853
- Maybe not, miss.
- Mrs.

290
00:31:23,165 --> 00:31:26,398
Pell. Her old man's Ray Stuckey's deputy.

291
00:31:29,631 --> 00:31:31,612
But I'm single.

292
00:31:51,010 --> 00:31:53,095
Move out of the way.

293
00:31:55,702 --> 00:31:59,769
Move over, boy.
We'll take care of this. It's a local problem.

294
00:31:59,874 --> 00:32:02,898
We'll handle this.
We don't need your damn help.

295
00:32:05,401 --> 00:32:09,885
It ain't right havin' blood on Main Street.
How'd that look on the TV news?

296
00:32:11,762 --> 00:32:14,161
- Get up.
- OK, I got him. I got him.

297
00:32:18,437 --> 00:32:20,105
He's the kid from the diner.

298
00:32:20,209 --> 00:32:23,546
Think twice before you talk to
coloured kids with an audience.

299
00:32:23,651 --> 00:32:27,092
They're sending a message from
the boss in Tupelo, and you know it.

300
00:32:27,196 --> 00:32:30,116
I know it, yes. Clayton Townley,
chief pointy head.

301
00:32:30,221 --> 00:32:33,454
Yeah, that's right. How did you know?

302
00:32:33,558 --> 00:32:35,852
Bureau procedure, Mr Ward.
Try it sometime.

303
00:32:35,956 --> 00:32:37,625
We did.

304
00:32:37,729 --> 00:32:40,232
We found the car the kids were driving.

305
00:33:20,590 --> 00:33:22,676
Good morning.

306
00:33:31,436 --> 00:33:33,418
Good morning.

307
00:34:54,030 --> 00:34:57,680
Two beer cans, a Coca-Cola bottle,
a green plastic bottle...

308
00:34:57,784 --> 00:35:03,311
...a badly burned wristwatch stopped
at 12.45, and a set of keys. No bodies.

309
00:35:03,416 --> 00:35:07,796
- I want the area searched. Every inch.
- Yes, sir.

310
00:35:07,900 --> 00:35:10,611
- It's a big swamp.
- Every inch, Mr Bird.

311
00:35:14,678 --> 00:35:17,286
I guess they never left Mississippi.

312
00:35:18,641 --> 00:35:21,144
They're dead. They're dead.

313
00:35:22,291 --> 00:35:24,168
Mr Bird?

314
00:35:24,273 --> 00:35:28,027
- Yes, sir?
- There's a telephone at the truck stop.

315
00:35:28,131 --> 00:35:32,615
Get to it, get on it, and get me
a hundred more men here by morning.

316
00:35:33,137 --> 00:35:35,223
- A hundred?
- A hundred.

317
00:35:35,640 --> 00:35:38,768
- Bureau people, sir?
- I don't care if it's the army!

318
00:35:38,873 --> 00:35:42,105
- I want this entire swamp searched!
- Yes, sir.

319
00:35:45,234 --> 00:35:47,528
Don't do it, Mr Ward.

320
00:35:47,633 --> 00:35:51,491
- You'll just start a war.
- It was a war long before we got here.

321
00:36:49,891 --> 00:36:52,394
Get the fuck outta here now!

322
00:37:33,065 --> 00:37:35,150
Sir?

323
00:37:35,985 --> 00:37:40,782
The sheriff's alibi is solid. He was playing
poker with his wife's brother and cousins.

324
00:37:40,886 --> 00:37:44,849
- The whole time?
- For three hours. He lost $11.38.

325
00:37:46,518 --> 00:37:51,210
There's something else. We're having
a little trouble with the motel manager.

326
00:37:51,315 --> 00:37:55,799
- What kind of trouble?
- He wants us out. We're bad for business.

327
00:37:55,903 --> 00:37:57,885
Buy it.

328
00:37:57,989 --> 00:38:00,492
- Sorry, sir?
- Buy it!

329
00:38:01,535 --> 00:38:03,516
The motel.

330
00:38:03,620 --> 00:38:06,227
- How high can I go?
- Whatever it takes.

331
00:38:30,109 --> 00:38:32,507
Today in Jessup County, Mississippi...

332
00:38:32,612 --> 00:38:36,157
...amidst the violence of this week,
the eyes of the nation...

333
00:38:36,262 --> 00:38:40,224
...are fixed on the search
for the missing civil rights workers.

334
00:38:40,537 --> 00:38:45,439
I think it's all a big hoax. But if they
are in that swamp, then they asked for it.

335
00:38:45,543 --> 00:38:51,591
Naval reserves have joined FBI
agents in searching for the missing men.

336
00:38:51,696 --> 00:38:56,284
I think they planned it. They're sittin' up in
New York laughin' at us Mississippi folks.

337
00:38:56,389 --> 00:39:01,499
- You think it's a hoax?
- A big hoax. They gonna find nothin'.

338
00:39:01,603 --> 00:39:05,983
Civil rights leaders are optimistic
as to the young men's whereabouts.

339
00:39:06,087 --> 00:39:10,676
But privately there is mounting concern
that they will ever be found alive.

340
00:39:10,780 --> 00:39:13,491
They came lookin' for trouble
and found it.

341
00:39:13,596 --> 00:39:17,976
This is Marek Baribobi, Network News,
Jessup County, Mississippi.

342
00:39:20,270 --> 00:39:24,858
Tell you what I think they oughta be doin'.
Lookin' up in Canada for them boys...

343
00:39:24,963 --> 00:39:27,570
...instead of our swamps around here.

344
00:39:27,674 --> 00:39:33,201
I'll tell you somethin' else. I think it's
a stunt dreamed up by NAAC people.

345
00:39:33,306 --> 00:39:36,226
- NAAC people?
- NAACP.

346
00:39:36,330 --> 00:39:41,335
Know what it stands for? Niggers,
Alligators, Apes, Coons and Possums.

347
00:39:41,440 --> 00:39:44,151
Tell you what you got.
You got your NAACP.

348
00:39:44,255 --> 00:39:48,010
You got your SNCC. You got your COFO.

349
00:39:48,114 --> 00:39:52,703
You know what all that mess is?
B-U-L-L-S-H-I-T.

350
00:39:52,807 --> 00:39:54,893
You got it?

351
00:39:58,543 --> 00:40:04,070
One day we won't have to say
"Good morning, sir, Mr Sheriff."

352
00:40:04,174 --> 00:40:08,450
Maybe there'll come a time when
we won't have to say "Mr Stuckey".

353
00:40:08,554 --> 00:40:13,038
One day there'll come a time when
we'll just say "Stuckey" or "Sheriff".

354
00:40:13,142 --> 00:40:17,731
And one day there'll come a time when
the sheriff won't even be a white man.

355
00:40:29,202 --> 00:40:30,975
Hello.

356
00:40:34,312 --> 00:40:37,024
I wonder if I could ask you
a few questions.

357
00:40:37,128 --> 00:40:41,612
I don't suppose you could tell me
what kind of flower these are, could you?

358
00:40:41,717 --> 00:40:44,741
I been seein' 'em
all over the place here and...

359
00:40:45,784 --> 00:40:48,599
Never saw such a darn pretty plant.

360
00:40:49,642 --> 00:40:51,519
They're trumpet-pitchers.

361
00:40:51,624 --> 00:40:53,605
Trumpet-pitchers?

362
00:40:53,918 --> 00:40:56,421
They're beautiful. They really are.

363
00:40:56,734 --> 00:41:00,071
They don't smell so good
but they're pretty.

364
00:41:04,346 --> 00:41:06,432
It's nice talkin' to you.

365
00:41:06,536 --> 00:41:11,542
Sorry about interruptin' your meeting
but we can't get anybody to talk to us.

366
00:41:11,646 --> 00:41:13,732
They zip up, like my momma used to say.

367
00:41:13,836 --> 00:41:18,738
People don't wanna talk to you because
they're afraid it'll get back to the law.

368
00:41:18,842 --> 00:41:21,554
<i>- We are the law.
- Not around here you ain't.</i>

369
00:41:22,388 --> 00:41:28,645
We came to find out what happened to
those boys. They were here to help you.

370
00:41:28,749 --> 00:41:33,546
- It ain't coloured folks you should talk to.
- Who should we talk to?

371
00:41:34,381 --> 00:41:36,466
Come on, Aaron.

372
00:41:37,405 --> 00:41:40,533
You should start with the sheriff's office.

373
00:41:41,993 --> 00:41:44,913
<i>- Why aren't you afraid?
- How come you ain't?</i>

374
00:41:45,018 --> 00:41:46,791
Aaron?

375
00:41:47,833 --> 00:41:50,545
Aaron, come on, son.

376
00:42:03,268 --> 00:42:08,273
<i>Here's the pitch. Swing and a line-drive
base hit. Another run is home.</i>

377
00:42:12,028 --> 00:42:15,260
<i>On to the next pitch by the ruffled
Bob Gibson. He is upset.</i>

378
00:42:15,365 --> 00:42:18,285
<i>Ron Hunt singled to centre.
Hickman passed third...</i>

379
00:42:18,389 --> 00:42:20,579
<i>... and scored the Mets' second run.</i>

380
00:42:20,683 --> 00:42:23,290
<i>Hunt holds on at first,
and the Mets lead two to one.</i>

381
00:42:35,805 --> 00:42:40,080
Good evening, Mrs Pell. I'm Agent Ward.
This is Agent Anderson.

382
00:42:40,184 --> 00:42:42,479
We're with the FBI.

383
00:42:42,583 --> 00:42:44,669
Is your husband home?

384
00:42:44,773 --> 00:42:47,172
We'd like to have a word with him.

385
00:42:47,902 --> 00:42:49,987
Y'all come in, then.

386
00:42:56,453 --> 00:43:00,937
It's the FBI gentlemen, Clinton. They
wanna ask you some more questions.

387
00:43:01,042 --> 00:43:03,336
You want me to put
your dinner in the oven?

388
00:43:06,047 --> 00:43:08,550
Leave us alone.

389
00:43:08,654 --> 00:43:10,740
Mind if I take a seat?

390
00:43:14,599 --> 00:43:17,727
What's so goddamn important
you got to bother me at home?

391
00:43:17,831 --> 00:43:22,629
I just wanted to run through once again
your movements on June 21st.

392
00:43:22,733 --> 00:43:24,923
June which?

393
00:43:25,027 --> 00:43:27,113
June 21st.

394
00:43:27,217 --> 00:43:32,223
Deputy, we both know what day we're
talking about, so let's do this civilised.

395
00:43:32,327 --> 00:43:36,707
Then you get back to your ball game
and we can get back to Washington.

396
00:43:47,240 --> 00:43:49,743
Please, don't let me interrupt you.

397
00:43:50,577 --> 00:43:56,104
It's just when you've heard a question
a dozen times, it gets kinda boring.

398
00:43:56,626 --> 00:43:58,920
Yeah, I guess so.

399
00:44:05,281 --> 00:44:08,618
- You don't eat together?
- He works funny hours.

400
00:44:11,643 --> 00:44:13,728
- You think that's odd?
- No.

401
00:44:13,833 --> 00:44:16,231
No, I work funny hours myself.

402
00:44:19,151 --> 00:44:22,280
I eat when I'm hungry.
He eats when he can.

403
00:44:22,384 --> 00:44:25,930
- Can I get you somethin'?
- No, no. Thanks.

404
00:44:26,034 --> 00:44:28,015
This is a nice house.

405
00:44:28,120 --> 00:44:31,352
- How long have you lived here?
- I was born here.

406
00:44:31,457 --> 00:44:35,107
But my father lost the house
in a poker game a long time ago.

407
00:44:37,088 --> 00:44:40,008
We've been payin' rent ever since.

408
00:44:42,824 --> 00:44:45,535
It's a wicked game.

409
00:44:48,038 --> 00:44:49,811
Poker.

410
00:44:50,854 --> 00:44:52,939
Wicked.

411
00:44:53,044 --> 00:44:55,025
Mr Anderson?

412
00:44:57,737 --> 00:45:00,448
It's nice talkin' to you. Guess I gotta go.

413
00:45:04,724 --> 00:45:07,539
Them pork chops still any good, honey?
Bring me a beer.

414
00:45:07,644 --> 00:45:09,938
Good night.

415
00:45:10,564 --> 00:45:12,545
Let you get back to your baseball.

416
00:45:12,649 --> 00:45:16,299
They say it's the only game
where a black man can wave a stick...

417
00:45:16,404 --> 00:45:18,489
I know. I already heard that one.

418
00:45:24,538 --> 00:45:27,771
Fifty minutes of his alibi
hinges on his wife.

419
00:45:27,875 --> 00:45:31,108
- You talked to her. What's she like?
- She's a nice lady.

420
00:45:31,212 --> 00:45:34,862
Tell me, Mr Anderson.
How does a woman like that end up with...

421
00:45:34,966 --> 00:45:38,825
With shithead in there? You know
what these small towns are like.

422
00:45:38,929 --> 00:45:43,413
A girl spends all her time in high school
lookin' for the guy she's gonna marry...

423
00:45:43,518 --> 00:45:46,021
...and spends the rest
of her life wonderin' why.

424
00:45:46,125 --> 00:45:48,732
Something's wrong. He's too confident.

425
00:45:48,836 --> 00:45:51,652
- Did you see the wedding photograph?
- No.

426
00:45:51,756 --> 00:45:55,719
His three pals, the ushers,
had their thumbs hooked in their belts...

427
00:45:55,823 --> 00:45:58,535
...with their three fingers pointing down.

428
00:45:58,639 --> 00:46:01,246
So what is that?
Some sort of Masonic thing?

429
00:46:01,351 --> 00:46:04,271
No! KKK.

430
00:46:09,693 --> 00:46:12,822
I know you ain't drunk.

431
00:46:12,926 --> 00:46:16,055
- I'm not drunk.
- All right. You ain't drunk.

432
00:46:16,159 --> 00:46:19,600
I'm just gonna take you
where you can sleep it off.

433
00:46:19,705 --> 00:46:21,790
All right. Hold up.

434
00:46:24,815 --> 00:46:26,900
Watch your head.

435
00:47:20,920 --> 00:47:26,030
Hi. Uh... There was a couple of things
I needed to check with you.

436
00:47:26,134 --> 00:47:30,931
- My husband's not here.
- Actually, it was you I wanted to talk to.

437
00:47:31,661 --> 00:47:33,956
Me?

438
00:47:34,060 --> 00:47:36,563
OK. You'd better come in, then.

439
00:47:40,526 --> 00:47:42,507
Just take a minute.

440
00:47:42,611 --> 00:47:45,740
My boss, he's kind of a pain.
A college kid.

441
00:47:45,844 --> 00:47:49,703
He has to dot all the i's
and cross all the t's.

442
00:47:49,807 --> 00:47:55,230
- What is it you wanted to ask me about?
- It's a time thing we're not so clear about.

443
00:47:55,334 --> 00:47:58,358
Should I put your flowers
in some water while you're here?

444
00:47:58,463 --> 00:48:00,548
Yeah. Actually they're for you.

445
00:48:01,800 --> 00:48:04,198
They're beautiful.

446
00:48:04,303 --> 00:48:06,388
They are pretty, aren't they?

447
00:48:06,493 --> 00:48:09,413
They don't smell so nice
but they're pretty.

448
00:48:09,934 --> 00:48:12,437
Can I get you anything? Some tea?

449
00:48:12,541 --> 00:48:14,627
Yeah. Thanks.

450
00:48:29,853 --> 00:48:32,981
Oh, don't you look at that.
It's a terrible photo.

451
00:48:33,085 --> 00:48:35,588
Oh, I don't know about that.

452
00:48:36,423 --> 00:48:39,864
- Is this recent?
- No. I wish.

453
00:48:39,968 --> 00:48:42,575
Well... this here looks recent to me.

454
00:48:42,680 --> 00:48:45,287
We were married 14 years ago.

455
00:48:45,391 --> 00:48:48,311
Are you kidding me? No! Come on.

456
00:48:49,875 --> 00:48:51,961
- You take sugar?
- Sure do.

457
00:48:53,525 --> 00:48:57,905
- You know, I grew up in a town like this.
- You were smart enough to leave.

458
00:48:58,010 --> 00:48:59,887
Why didn't you?

459
00:48:59,991 --> 00:49:02,077
"For better or for worse."

460
00:49:06,039 --> 00:49:08,647
How about you? Are you married?

461
00:49:10,315 --> 00:49:13,027
Well, I was, as I remember.

462
00:49:14,069 --> 00:49:16,781
It didn't last very long. I was never home.

